1 Introduction

In general, cutting stock problems (CSPs) address the issue of how to cut some required pieces from some material stock while minimizing waste.

These problems have applications in operations research. Some examples include cutting wood lumber [KS22] and fabric cutting [Sha+19].

Some variations include orthogonal problems, where -dimensional rectangles are cut from larger -dimensional rectangles, or non-orthogonal problems, where cut-outs can be any shape.

A natural specialization of the one-dimensional cutting stock problem is the binary cutting stock problem (BCSP), where each required item (henceforth called an order) only has a demand of 1. This is equivalent to the bin-packing problem, where items of fixed sizes are packed into an infinite number of bins while minimizing the number of bins used.

The BCSP/bin packing problem has obvious applications in shipping and transport, but also in resource allocation on computer systems such as FPGAs [Kro+20] and data centres [BB10].

For a more in-depth review of these problems, see [DIM16]. This paper aims to explain and implement the results of [Van+94], where the authors combine branch-and-bound methods with column generation to create so-called branch-and-price methods for binary cutting stock problems.

We present the one-dimensional binary cutting stock problem:

A factory has an unlimited stock of -inch long paper rolls that can be cut into smaller lengths. They receive orders of paper rolls of length . Assuming both trim loss and overproduction are waste, how do we fill the orders while minimizing waste?

4 Delayed Column Generation

Instead of trying to solve (5) outright, we could try building our way up. Let a general restricted master problem be defined similarly to (5), but for . So,

The idea behind delayed column generation1 is as follows:

  1. Start with some .
  2. Solve (6) for .
  3. Check whether the given solution is an optimal solution of (5).
  4. If not, extend to and repeat from step 2.

Out of these steps, step 1 requires some short discussion, step 2 is done using an out-of-the-box solver, and steps 3 and 4 are the main difficulty behind column generation.

4.1 Generating

Recall that corresponds to the set of all patterns to cut a roll of length . Therefore, should correspond to a feasible set of orders which satisfy (5). The method we will use is called the First-Fit Decreasing (FFD) heuristic [Van+94]. This involves sorting the orders in decreasing order of size, and greedily cutting them into rolls, only adding new rolls when the last one has no more space.

4.2 Duality

Suppose we have solved the reduced linear master problem (6). We now want to check whether or not this corresponds to an optimal solution of (5). Furthermore, if it is not optimal, we want to extend the reduced pattern set in a thoughtful way.

Consider the dual of the full linear master problem (5)

and the dual of the reduced master problem (6)

The equalities in the brackets follow from the Strong Duality Theorem [Hau25].

When solving the Reduced Master Problem (RPM), the solver simultaneously produces an optimal primal solution and a corresponding dual solution . Because the restricted master problem (RPM) is a restriction of the full minimization master problem, its optimal objective value satisfies .2

Consequently, the reduced dual solution obtained from the RPM is either dual-feasible for the full master problem or violates at least one of its dual constraints.

This is noteworthy because it allows us to verify the optimality of a restricted solution by checking whether the dual solution violates any of the dual constraints, each of which is associated with a pattern.

At first sight, this problem still seems intractable. We have dual constraints to check, which is still an exponential problem. However, it is not necessary to check every constraint explicitly. Instead, it is enough to identify the most violated constraint.

Another interpretation of the dual variables is as prices. Each dual column is an order, and each constraint guarantees that the total value of the orders cut from an item is less than the cost of introducing the pattern.

Therefore, finding the most violated constraint corresponds to finding the pattern which maximizes the value of the orders included, subject to a length limit . This is exactly the knapsack problem.

We now have two cases.

Suppose the largest cost . Then, the pattern with highest cost still does not violate the constraints on the full dual problem. This implies that the reduced dual solution is feasible for the full dual problem, which then implies that the reduced primal solution is an optimal solution for the full linear master problem. This terminates our column generation procedure.

5 Branch-and-Price

Now that we have a method to solve the LP relaxation of our problem, we need a way to leverage this for the more restricted integer problem.

First we will outline the general branch-and-bound technique, and then discuss how to modify it to suit a column generation approach.

Now we apply this to the cutting stock problem.

5.2 Ryan-Foster Branching

Recall that we are solving (4), where the primal variables correspond to whether or not a pattern is chosen. A branching rule is a set of extra restrictions imposed on the child nodes IP, which is then relaxed to an LP.

A good branching rule should be guaranteed to find an integer solution, and be easy to implement into any sub-problems (in our case, the knapsack problem).

The general recommended approach is to find this , and fix to be either or . In our case, this would correspond to no longer picking a pattern from then on. However, this is quite an ineffective rule, because if we fix , the column generation algorithm could, and most likely would, re-generate that pattern.

Another naive approach would be to branch on fixing and for some and all patterns. However, the branch would always produce an infeasible solution, since there needs to be at least one pattern which produces order .

The authors of [RF81] introduce a novel branching approach, now eponymously called Ryan-Foster branching, where we branch on whether two orders can be cut from the same pattern.

Then, we have the following lemma, which is equivalent to [Van+94, Prop. 2].

Lemma8 therefore naturally generates a branching strategy for fractional solutions:

These branches will be called the -branch and the -branch respectively. Since , the branching constraint on the -branch is that either or , but not both for all . Analogously, the -branch has that .

This branching rule moves the restriction from the primal variables to the patterns themselves, which are generated by solving the knapsack problem. This means that our knapsack problem now has extra constraints, which we will deal with in the next section.

5.3 The Knapsack Problem with Ryan-Foster Constraints

Recall the knapsack problem (10) used to find new patterns to add during the column generation approach. Now that we are using Ryan-Foster branching, the patterns we can generate are further restricted. Fortunately, the two different types of constraints can be dealt with separately.

The -branch constraints, where for all patterns, are quite easy to adapt. In the knapsack problem, we remove the two items corresponding to orders and , and replace them with a new order with , . This is a larger order which forces the two items to be taken together. In the case where we have several of these constraints chained together (so ), then we can just sum them all together.

The -branch constraints are a bit tougher. If we have just one of these constraints , then we can solve the knapsack problem twice, once for , and once for , and take the best solution from both.

However, if we have several of these constraints linked together, the structure is a bit more complicated. Relationships of the form and cannot be taken together can be represented by an undirected graph , where .

This problem is not trivial, and is an area of active research [PS09]. In the interests of time, we have elected to use an out-of-the-box IP solver, the details of which will now be discussed.

6 Practical Implementation Details

The implementation splits the branch-and-price method into:

  1. a restricted master LP solved with column generation,
  2. a pricing problem solved as a 0/1 knapsack with Ryan-Foster constraints,
  3. a branch-and-bound algorithm to solve the IP using the LP.

6.1 Data structures and helper routines

Patterns are represented as tuples of integers type Pattern = tuple[int, ...], and their corresponding variables accessed through a dictionary dict[Pattern: LpVariable].

Branching restrictions are stored using two structures:

  • A conflict graph , implemented using the networkx package [HSS08].

  • A Union-Find Set [Cor+22] implemented by hand. It has two sub-routines:

    • find(i) returns the root of element . Two elements have the same root if and only if they are bound to be equal in generated patterns.
    • unite(i, j) sets elements and to have the same root.

6.2 Nodes and the restricted master problem

Each node in the branch-and-bound tree is represented by a Node object. It owns a restricted master LP solved using column generation, a DSU, a conflict graph, and upper and lower bounds. The master problem is implemented exactly as in (5).

The Node class supports adding columns incrementally by adding a new variable to the LP corresponding to a pattern, as well as modifying all of the constraints in-place.

6.3 Column generation

Node.column_gen() is a routine responsible for performing column generation for that node, as per Algorithm1. The restricted LP and the KRFC are solved using the Coin-or branch-and-cut mixed integer linear program solver [For+24].

The initial pattern set to start off the column generation is created using a subroutine p0_ryan_foster, which creates a feasible initial pattern set that still obeys the Ryan-Foster constraints.

6.4 Pricing using the KRFC

knapsack(values, weights, capacity, dsu, conflict_graph) implements pricing as an integer program

6.5 Possible Improvements

The implementation presented here is not yet fully optimized, as evidenced by the discrepancy in reported performance statistics (see next section) relative to the model in [Van+94]. There was an attempt to implement the following ideas, but they were not achieved in the interests of time.

  1. In the column generation phase, the master LP does not need to be solved to optimality. Using [Van+94, Prop. 3]), it is possible to terminate earlier, resulting in less columns being added, and less calls to the LP solver.

  2. Whenever it is necessary to branch, there are often many candidate pairs . Picking optimal pairs, especially for the -branch, can make a significant difference in runtime. The authors of [Van+94] picked pairs such that is as close to as possible to minimize waste.

  3. Since we are doing a depth-first traversal of the branch-and-bound tree, most nodes never pick up a -constraint, or if they do, only in small numbers. The KRFC can be optimized for only equality constraints in the case where the conflict graph is trivial, greatly speeding up knapsack steps.

  4. Our implementation restarts each new nodes columns using a heuristic. A warm start, where child nodes inherit the parents nodes, is likely quicker, but requires careful handling of inherited patterns which violate new constraints.

7 Computational Experiments

The code is written in Python, and is stored on GitHub at this link.

The following plots are generated from a series of profiling experiments, where the length is fixed at , is varied from 2 to 40, and orders are sampled from a discrete uniform distribution . Each of these experiments was done 30 times per value of . Three outliers were removed: .

For each value of , the distribution is skewed, with long tail times occurring frequently. This is likely due in combination to the fact that a) the times recorded are wall times, not CPU times and b) the random sampling of the order sizes means that some problems will be far more difficult to solve than others.

Figure1 shows the median total runtime of the branch_and_bound subroutine as increases. Noting the logarithmic scale on both axes, we see a roughly polynomial runtime complexity. The red line is a least-squares regression, and has a gradient of to the nearest thousandth, implying that runtime . Log-linear plots, where only the -axis has logarithmic scaling, show sub-exponential scaling with , further supporting the polynomial runtime3.

Figure3 shows the call graph of the solver. We see that 85% of the time is spent in Coin-or MILP solver, since both the knapsack and master problems call it. In this case, the knapsack problems took almost exactly twice as long on average to solve than the master LPs. Only 15% of the time was spent outside of the solvers, mostly on setting up problems (__mul__, __rmul__ and __init__) and on initializing the classes in Python.

Figure2 shows that the knapsack problems take an increasingly longer amount of time to solve relative to the master LP problems. This is likely due to the increased number of constraints from deeper tree traversals, while the master-LP problem does not change in form or complexity for large . Furthermore, the knapsack problem is solved as an integer problem, requiring the branch-and-cut solver to be called rather than the linear program solver.

8 Conclusions

This paper presents and implements a branch-and-price method for the one-dimensional binary cutting stock problem. We begin by converting the overly symmetric problem to a Dantzig-Wolfe master problem reformulation. Next, the LP relaxation is defined, and a delayed column generation approach is introduced, where the exponentially large set of patterns is reduced, and new patterns are generated on demand by solving a knapsack sub-problem.

Next, general branch-and-bound methods are discussed. Convergence and pruning results are proved, and an example algorithm is laid out. The branch-and-price method, a combination of column generation and branch-and-bound, is explored, and Ryan-Foster branching is used used for non-degenerate but still feasible branching rules.

We then outline a computational implementation. A Union-Find Set along with an undirected graph are used to represent the Ryan-Foster constraints for every node, and a subroutine is defined which greedily finds the pairs of orders to branch on. Limitations and improvements are also discussed.

Finally, we perform a series of computational experiments. The problem is shown to exhibit polynomial scaling relative to the number of orders. Over 80% of the time is spent solving sub-problems rather than in the Python logic code. The knapsack problem is shown to be the main limitation, with roughly twice the amount of time being spent on it compared to the reduced master LPs.
